<br>
Things that are hard just to be hard are annoying, no fun, bad game design, and a major detraction to gameplay. Having to cancel every darn buff you have to lose one debuff would qualify as that. The incredibly annoying corpse runs at level 3, when you were still totally clueless and learning the game, because you really couldn't afford to lose that rusty sword you just looted, were meaningless punishment for player unfamiliarity with game controls more often than they were an enriching roleplay experience. I don't know HOW many times I cleared that darn kobold camp just so newbies could get their bodies back after wandering too close and getting smacked. The incredible difficulty in getting a bind for non-casters used to be just a stupid way to make some classes artificially needed - the NPC soulbinders are a nice solution to that.<br>
<br>
Things that are hard because they add to the flavor and depth of the game are an attractant (at least to some people). The FV language rules are that, for example. The price of not being able to easily communicate with everyone all the time is well worth it - in exchange for a greater immersion in the feel of a fantasy world and giving language skills actual value other than &quot;look, I learned Orc... whee!&quot;. The minor annoyance and roadblocks imposed by the TLC are more than tolerable, given the major dent in farming and ubercamping as a result. Naming policy enforcement results in occasional overbearing stupidity, but saves us from meeting &quot;Bob17&quot; the elf, &quot;Urmom Sux&quot; the wizard, and &quot;L33t Mc0wnz0r&quot; the PvP-enabled player on a daily basis.<br>
<br>
Other online games are making many of the same decisions of late - Asheron's Call revamped their newbie experience lately, and quite well, for just these sorts of reasons - and is making many of the same sorts of streamlining changes to address long-term annoyance factors in the game. Yes, some of the playerbase out there just wants to be uber - but assuming that every player complaint out there is baseless and motivated by greed is the path of ruin for a gaming company. Class balance issues, game mechanic frustrations, and even cosmetic look-and-feel requests are not automatically invalid just because first or frequently noted by players.<br>
